After adding CD2 into the IC solution, the UV–vis spectra of IC were recorded under natural light radiation with varying time. The degradation of IC by CD2 was studied according to a pseudo-first-order reaction and its kinetic equation can be expressed as In(C0/C) = kt, where C0 is the initial concentration of the dyes, and Ct is the concentrations of the dyes after degradation for t min, k is the apparent rate constant. As shown in Fig. 6
                        A, the time dependent UV–vis spectra for IC was recorded, the maximum absorption peak of IC at 611 nm gradually decreases with the delay of time after adding CD2. The corresponding plot of ln (Ct/C0) vs. time for IC under the photocatalysis of CD2 can be seen in Fig. 6B, it can be seen that the photocatalytic degradation IC is well fitted with pseudo first-order kinetics equation and the degradation rate constant is 0.0309 min−1. Furthermore, as can be seen in Fig. 6C, the catalytic degradation reaction of IC within 120 min also can be certified by the solution color change from blue to transparent. In short, IC can be well degraded by CD2 under natural light with the degradation efficiency up to 97%. To further evaluate the photocatalytic activity of CD2 on the degradation of IC, a cycling test was carried out by continual supplements of IC in CD2 solution. Cycling runs for the IC photocatalytic degradation over CD2 was performed with the same time interval (Fig. 7
                        ). It can be observed that the degradation efficiency of CD2 on IC can still reach 93% after three cycles of repeated use. Moreover, after five recycling times, the degradation efficiency can get to above 90%. It can be deduced that CD2 can be reused directly without separation.
